265. quoniam in Tusculanum ire constituit: cf. ad Att. IV. 16, 3: multo eqo maqis hoe mihi cavendum putavi (i. e. ne hominem id aetatis in tam lonqo sermone diutius retinerem) in Scaevola, qui et aetate et valetudine erat ea, qua eum esse memmium et eis honoribus, ut vix satis decorum videretur eum pluris dies esse in Crassi Tusculano. The departure of Scaevola also gives suitable occasion for the introduction of C. Iulius Caesar Strabo, who takes part in the second day's conversation. — constituissem me venturum 1.. Aelio: cf. 58, 250: in rem praesentem, and. the passages there cited. Aelim, mentioned in 43, 193. — quam iucundus: Scaevola keeps up his charanteristic good nature (cf. 9, 35) to the last, and eloses with a retort upon Antony in which wit and eompliment are gracefully combined.
